messages.content: @rpanic 👀

It appears to be caused by my library using the same 'contract' instance between multiple consecutive tx, this eventually causes some of my library components to have access to some form of an 'outdated' contract instance, where the address appears malformed.

I have not pinpointed how this can happen on the snarky side, but if i use the 'latest' contract instance in every nested crevice of our library it works.
Okay I am also reusing instances, I will try it to confirm 👍
Woah that's a nice find! I thought this aspect was pretty robust, keep me updated about the details
I cannot confirm that, used new instances everytime and the error still occurs
for me it helped that i 'updated' the reference to contract/this in different places where i passed the instance to my components
i still wonder what happens internally that makes this happen
is there some lifecycle or something that populates `this.address` in Mina.transaction or something?
If I read the snarkyjs sourcecode correct this.address is not part of any proved witness, it is passed in as a constant
It is just directly set by the parameter you pass into the constructor
I'd say that is not expected behavious tbh

Ok so I see that this.address is also used to create the `self` AccountUpdate. Can we assume that that way `this.address` cannot be tampered with and is always the same as the publicKey of the current AU? @gregor
all of that is fine but doesnt explain while at some point i am not able to call .toBase58() on it
Yeah but maybe we get a better understand where that data is accessed - i.e. could get corrupted

Yes and no @rpanic. In proofs, `this.address` is a variable and can be changed by the prover without modifying the circuit: https://github.com/o1-labs/snarkyjs/blob/8ddb6f984a270f6aa87ed245b5f21c3fa81577ec/src/lib/zkapp.ts#L131-L135
This is a good thing IMO, because it means that we don't have to pass in the address as input to `SmartContract.compile()`. The circuits are not tied to the address they are deployed to
i think it has to do with enabling proofs and the address being overwriten during that
see i thought so
But it can't be tampered with because the same `this.address` is also put as public key into the account update
Okay nice, that was my question
So whatever value the proof gets, is also the account that the proof applies to

for me i use a single instance of my contract, and i pass it to my libraries. this works for deploy & first tx. but then in the second tx, in i dont know which callback run etc, address.toBase58() stops working. I fixed it by ensurnig all of my library has access to the latest contract instance at all times
Very interesting, sounds definitely related to how we pass in the address
also what explains that it works for the first two tx is the fact that deployment isnt proven
Deployment is never proven
Except you have deployed previously
@maht0rz does it fail during the first proof, or during the second?
Or not inside the prover at all?
during the second proof, i suspect the address is tampered with in the prover of the first tx
that sounds about right i think
due to the stale reference probably or smtn

the flow of a tx is:
- run the tx callback twice (store method arguments for zkapp provers)
- during `tx.prove()`, run those methods again, as part of the prover (this doesn't run the tx callback -- just the individual methods that need a proof)
plus the most important thing is that the prover is entirely separate from the active contract instance, since its static
yeah! the prover gets a fresh contract instance
btw that is probably the thing that surprised me the most
bcs i made our lib to work 'with instances' and then i start to compile/prove and my dreams fall apart 😄
haha yeah. the methods in some sense are more like static methods actually. But then we couldn't use all those nice APIs with `this.something`. It's a bit of an abuse of how classes are designed
Classes kinda don't fit the model that we need, but then they mentally and API-wise somehow make sense.. I don't know
ok, wen prover caching?
not today 😄
is serialising the prover a problem?
I fixed the unwrap error by wrapping one of my inputs into `UInt.from(x.toString())`. So it seems your hunch was right
maybe as a first step snarkyjs can by default clone all structs and fields when calling a Smartcontract method?
we already do that but there seems to be some problem with that

But I could do more digging what exactly goes wrong
